name: Domestic Violence
overview:
Domestic violence and emotional abuse are behaviors used in an intimate or dating relationship to control the other. Partners may be married or not; heterosexual or gay, lesbian or transgendered; living together, separated or dating. Some common examples are hitting, shoving, kicking, slapping, threatening to harm, throwing objects, scaring the other person, name-calling, andstalking. 

If you are in immediate danger, call 911. For domestic violence assistance, call the Domestic Violence Action Center legal helpline at 808-531-3771 or 1-800-690-6200 (Toll-free). It is available between 8:30am-4:30pm Mon-Fri.

name: Child support
overview: Both the court and the Child Support Service Division (CSSD) have the authority to issue child support orders.  However, the child support orders come about in different ways.  The court must issue a child support order when it decides a parenting plan ( the custody and visitation arrangement)  for a child in a case involving divorce, dissolution, or custody between unmarried parents.  The CSSD issues an order when one parent requests child support because the parents have split up and the parent taking care of the child(ren) wants the other parent to pay support for the child.  Sometimes a parent will have a CSSD support order and then file a custody case in court later.  If the court issues a child support order that is different from the CSSD order, the court’s child support order takes priority and replaces the CSSD order.

overview: Sometimes one side in the case does not follow the court order.  To get that person to comply, there are different options.  Generally the first step is to file a written request to the opposing party asking them to do what the order says by a specific date. Hopefully he/she will follow the order and you won't need to go back to court.  If he or she does not cooperate, the next step is to let the court know by filing a motion. The type of motion depends on the specifics of what the court ordered and what the opposing party did or didn't do about following the order. Your motion usually asks the court to issue an order telling the opposing party to do something specific.  There is a specific process to collect money that is ordered to be paid.

name: Custody / Visitation
overview: After a court issues a parenting plan or custody order, there could be a change of circumstances by one or both parents or the children that require modifying the parenting plan.  Also, the child support order may need to be modified if there is a change in the parenting plan or a change in one or both parents' incomes.  Parents can always modify the parenting plan by agreement but the court needs to find a change of circumstances to order a modification.  The court needs to modify the child support order if warranted.

name: Domestic Violence
overview: If you have a court case involving children such as a divorce or custody case between unmarried parents, it is important to understand that a history of domestic violence by one or both parents can impact the parenting plan that the court orders.  The law presumes that the parent who committed the domestic violence might not get custody and visitation unless he or she meets certain requirements. These may include completing a batterer’s intervention or substance abuse treatment program. To find domestic violence, the law does not require the existence of a protective order or criminal charges. The divorce or custody judge may ask about domestic violence.  If there has been domestic violence, talking to a lawyer can help you understand how this law will impact your case.

name: Domestic Violence
overview: A domestic violence protective order is a court order that prohibits someone from committing domestic violence against another person and often includes provisions to have no contact and stay away from their home, work place, school or other specified locations.  There is a process to request a protective order that involves filing a petition to request either a 20-day order  or a one-year order or commonly both types.  There is usually one or two hearings depending on whether both orders are requested.  If the court grants the orders, they will include restrictions on the other side, if they have children together may address temporary custody, visitation and child support and may address other financial issues such as paying medical bills or rent.

name: Child Abuse
overview: The case is not over until the judge issues the final paperwork.  These documents are called Findings of Fact and Conclusions of Law and Final Decree and Judgment.  If there are children of the marriage, there will also be a parenting plan or custody and visitation plan and a child support order.  Sometimes the judge announces the decision at the end of the trial in the courtroom but the decision needs to be put in writing.  It is important to understand who is responsible to write up the final documents.  Usually the judge will write them up when people are representing themselves in the case.  If there are lawyers involved, the judge may ask one of the lawyers to write up the final documents according to what the judge said in court.  Sometimes the judge may ask one of the people representing themselves to write up the documents.  Before you leave the courtroom after the trial, make sure you understand what you are responsible to do, both to follow the order and to know if you are supposed to write up the final documents.

name: Public Benefits
overview: Sometimes one or both people in the case are unhappy with the final decision in the case. It is important to understand that judges make decisions according to legal factors that are set out in the law and previous decisions from the Alaska Supreme Court that interpret the law. If you think the judge made a mistake that caused the outcome, you may have options to file something in court to address the issue. Be aware that just not liking the outcome does not mean the judge made a mistake. Also be aware that there are deadlines to take most actions and if you do not file the appropriate document in time, you may be unable to file it. Read below to see the options and timelines.

Problems with my landlord, home, or apartment
overview: In Alaska, if a tenant is not paying rent or violating the terms of the lease, the landlord may bring an action to evict the tenant from the property.  This is called an eviction or FED (forcible, entry and detainer).  There are legal requirements that the landlord must follow according to the law.  The tenant can assert defenses if the landlord violated the law.  There is a court process to evict a tenant that has two stages:  the eviction hearing to remove the tenant from the propertty and the damages stage where the landlord can ask the court for money if the tenant damaged the property or didn't pay the rent.

name: Debt Collection
overview: In Alaska a person or entity who is owed money can sue the person who owes the money in court.  There are two kinds of cases to sue someone for a debt:  small claims and a civil case to collect a debt.  There are different court rules for each type of case and a $10,000 limit on the amount someone can sue for in a small claims case.  Small claims cases use informal rules and civil cases to collect a debt use formal rules of civil procedure and evidence.

name: Legal Guardianship
overview: In Alaska, there is a court process called guardianship to appoint another person to make decisions when someone lacks capacity to make decisions themselves.  There is also a process called conservatorship to appoint someone to deal with the finances when someone is having trouble managing their money.  A full guardian has powers to make all decisions for another person including about their finances.  There are some limits on the types of decisions a guardian may make.

name: Name Changes
overview: In Alaska there is a court process and forms to change your name if you are an adult or a child.  For adults, you must follow the steps that notify the public of the new name and your current name by posting on the court's free legal notice website or another place if the court allows it.  If you are getting a divorce or dissolution, you can change your name to a maiden name through that case and do not need to file a separate name change case.  To change the name of a minor child, the process is more complex than for changing an adult's name.  The court must find a sufficient reason for the change  and either have both parents' consent or find good cause to move forward without the consent.
